    <title>Combined summary - Gavin's post-0.9 TODO list...</title>
    <updated>2023-06-07T16:04:13.550005+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2013-August/003139.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>In August 2013, Bitcoin developers were actively working on improving the network's security and scalability. The community was exploring different methods for prioritizing peers based on certain criteria to mitigate against attacks and improve network efficiency. Warren Togami Jr. proposed using source IP or subnet connection limits to mitigate against Denial-of-Service (DoS) attacks, while Mike Hearn proposed an automated heuristic-driven prioritization solution. Meanwhile, Gavin Andresen listed three non-0.9 code projects he was working on: smarter fee handling, "first double-spend" relaying and alerting, and whitepapers on increasing or removing the 1MB block size limit.However, there were concerns about user security and potential sybil attacks on the network. Peter Todd suggested creating "SPV honeypots" that could attract a disproportionate percentage of the total SPV population and make it easier to harm SPV nodes. Additionally, there were discussions about ways to harm Simplified Payment Verification (SPV) nodes, such as dropping deterministic percentages of transactions or flooding peers with useless garbage. There were also concerns about relying on a smaller subset of Bloom filtering nodes, with Warren Togami suggesting making non-Bloom peers okay only when plugged into power and using wifi. The email threads and mailing list posts provide insights into the ongoing developments and challenges faced by Bitcoin developers in maintaining security and improving the network's functionality. One email exchange discussed changes made in bitcoinj-0.10 release notes that required Bloom-capable (0.8+) peers by default and would disconnect from older nodes to avoid accidental bandwidth saturation on mobile devices. Another email exchange included a PGP encrypted message, but its contents were unclear without proper decryption.Overall, the email threads and mailing list posts highlight how the Bitcoin community was actively working to improve the network's performance and security, including developing anti-DoS frameworks, addressing concerns about Bloom filtering nodes, and exploring different methods for prioritizing peers. However, there were also concerns about user-security and potential sybil attacks on the network, as well as issues with battery life and bandwidth impact on mobile devices.</summary>
